Here's an example of how you can add a button at the bottom of an ImGui window, while keeping in mind that the ImGui window works separately from the main window:

```c++
// Define a boolean variable to hold the state of the bottom button
bool bPressed = false;

// Create a new ImGui window
ImGui::Begin("My ImGui Window");

// Display an image
ImGui::Image(myImage, ImVec2(100, 100));

// Add some spacing at the bottom of the window
ImGui::Dummy(ImVec2(0, 20));

// Center-align a button at the bottom of the window
ImGui::SetCursorPosX((ImGui::GetWindowSize().x - ImGui::CalcTextSize("My Button").x) / 2.0f);
if (ImGui::Button("My Button"))
{
    bPressed = true;
}

// Close the ImGui window
ImGui::End();

// Check if the button was pressed and perform any necessary actions
if (bPressed)
{
    // Do something...
}
```

In this example, we define a boolean variable `bPressed` to hold the state of the bottom button. We create a new ImGui window using `ImGui::Begin("My ImGui Window")`, and display an image using `ImGui::Image(myImage, ImVec2(100, 100))`.

We then add some spacing at the bottom of the window using `ImGui::Dummy(ImVec2(0, 20))`, and center-align a button at the bottom of the window using `ImGui::SetCursorPosX((ImGui::GetWindowSize().x - ImGui::CalcTextSize("My Button").x) / 2.0f)` and `ImGui::Button("My Button")`. We check if the button was pressed using `if (ImGui::Button("My Button"))`, and perform any necessary actions if the button was pressed.

Finally, we close the ImGui window using `ImGui::End()`.

`emplace_back` is generally considered to be better than `push_back` in certain situations because it can avoid unnecessary copies or moves of objects.

`push_back` adds a copy or move of the object being added to the vector. For example, if you have a vector of objects and you want to add a new object to the end of the vector, you might write something like this:

```
std::vector<Object> myVec;

Object newObj;
myVec.push_back(newObj);
```

In this case, the `newObj` is first copied or moved into the vector, and then the original object is destroyed. This can be inefficient if the object is expensive to copy or move.

`emplace_back`, on the other hand, constructs the object in place at the end of the vector using the provided arguments. For example:

```
std::vector<Object> myVec;

myVec.emplace_back(arg1, arg2, ...);
```

In this case, the new object is constructed directly at the end of the vector, without any intermediate copies or moves.

`emplace_back` can be particularly useful when your objects are large or expensive to copy or move, or when you need to construct an object with a specific set of arguments. However, `emplace_back` does require that your object be movable or copyable, and it can also be more complex to use with objects that have complex constructors or require initialization in multiple stages. In general, you should use `emplace_back` when it makes sense for your specific use case, but not necessarily as a default choice for all vector insertions.

